Certainly! To implement a secure token management module that adheres to the facade pattern, you can create a `TokenManager` class that encapsulates various operations related to JSON Web Tokens (JWT), rate limiting, and token blacklisting. This design will help maintain loose coupling between components and provide a clean interface for managing tokens.

Below is an example implementation of the `TokenManager` class in JavaScript:

### Step 1: Install Necessary Packages

You may need to install some libraries to handle JWT, rate limiting, and blacklisting. Using npm, you can install the following:

```bash
npm install jsonwebtoken express-rate-limit
```

### Step 2: Implementation of Supporting Classes

#### JWT Operations

```javascript
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

class JWTService {
    constructor(secret, expiresIn) {
        this.secret = secret;
        this.expiresIn = expiresIn;
    }

    generateToken(payload) {
        return jwt.sign(payload, this.secret, { expiresIn: this.expiresIn });
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        try {
            return jwt.verify(token, this.secret);
        } catch (error) {
            throw new Error('Invalid token');
        }
    }
}
```

#### Rate Limiting

```javascript
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

class RateLimiter {
    constructor(maxRequests, windowMs) {
        this.limiter = rateLimit({
            windowMs: windowMs,
            max: maxRequests,
        });
    }

    getMiddleware() {
        return this.limiter;
    }
}
```

#### Token Blacklisting

```javascript
class TokenBlacklist {
    constructor() {
        this.blacklistedTokens = new Set();
    }

    add(token) {
        this.blacklistedTokens.add(token);
    }

    isBlacklisted(token) {
        return this.blacklistedTokens.has(token);
    }
}
```

### Step 3: TokenManager Class

Now, let's encapsulate these services in a `TokenManager` class:

```javascript
class TokenManager {
    constructor(jwtSecret, jwtExpiresIn, maxRequests, windowMs) {
        this.jwtService = new JWTService(jwtSecret, jwtExpiresIn);
        this.rateLimiter = new RateLimiter(maxRequests, windowMs);
        this.tokenBlacklist = new TokenBlacklist();
    }

    generateToken(payload) {
        return this.jwtService.generateToken(payload);
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        if (this.tokenBlacklist.isBlacklisted(token)) {
            throw new Error('Token is blacklisted');
        }
        return this.jwtService.verifyToken(token);
    }

    blacklistToken(token) {
        this.tokenBlacklist.add(token);
    }

    getRateLimitMiddleware() {
        return this.rateLimiter.getMiddleware();
    }
}
```

### Step 4: Using the TokenManager

You can use the `TokenManager` in your application as follows:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const tokenManager = new TokenManager('your_jwt_secret', '1h', 100, 15 * 60 * 1000); // 100 requests per 15 minutes

app.use(tokenManager.getRateLimitMiddleware());

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
    // Authenticate user and generate token
    const user = { id: 1, username: 'test' }; // Example user
    const token = tokenManager.generateToken(user);
    res.json({ token });
});

app.post('/logout', (req, res) => {
    const token = req.headers['authorization'].split(' ')[1];
    tokenManager.blacklistToken(token);
    res.sendStatus(204);
});

app.get('/protected', (req, res) => {
    const token = req.headers['authorization'].split(' ')[1];
    try {
        const userData = tokenManager.verifyToken(token);
        res.json({ message: 'Protected data', user: userData });
    } catch (error) {
        res.status(401).json({ error: error.message });
    }
});

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

### Summary

In this implementation, the `TokenManager` class serves as a facade, encapsulating the details of JWT management, rate limiting, and token blacklisting. Clients interact with a simple interface while the underlying complexity remains hidden, promoting loose coupling. You can further enhance this implementation by adding persistence for blacklisted tokens, improving error handling, and integrating with your actual user authentication logic.

