To extend your token management module to handle different types of tokens (such as access tokens, refresh tokens, and API keys) while ensuring that each type can have its own validation rules and encryption methods, you can use the Strategy pattern.

The Strategy pattern will allow you to define a family of algorithms (in this case, different methods of generating, validating, and managing tokens) and make them interchangeable at runtime without changing the TokenManager interface.

### Step 1: Define Token Strategy Interfaces

First, you can define interfaces for your different token strategies. This ensures that each strategy implements the necessary methods for generating and verifying tokens.

```javascript
class TokenStrategy {
    generateToken(payload) {
        throw new Error('Method not implemented');
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        throw new Error('Method not implemented');
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Implement Token Strategies

Now, create concrete strategies for the different types of tokens.

#### Access Token Strategy

```javascript
class AccessTokenStrategy extends TokenStrategy {
    constructor(secret, expiresIn) {
        super();
        this.secret = secret;
        this.expiresIn = expiresIn;
    }

    generateToken(payload) {
        return jwt.sign(payload, this.secret, { expiresIn: this.expiresIn });
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        return jwt.verify(token, this.secret);
    }
}
```

#### Refresh Token Strategy

```javascript
class RefreshTokenStrategy extends TokenStrategy {
    constructor(secret, expiresIn) {
        super();
        this.secret = secret;
        this.expiresIn = expiresIn;
    }

    generateToken(payload) {
        return jwt.sign(payload, this.secret, { expiresIn: this.expiresIn });
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        return jwt.verify(token, this.secret);
    }
}
```

#### API Key Strategy

```javascript
class ApiKeyStrategy extends TokenStrategy {
    constructor(secret) {
        super();
        this.secret = secret;
    }

    generateToken(payload) {
        // Simple example, in real cases, you might use more complex logic
        return jwt.sign(payload, this.secret); // API keys may not have expiration
    }

    verifyToken(token) {
        return jwt.verify(token, this.secret);
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Update the TokenManager

Now that you have different strategies for tokens, update the `TokenManager` to work with these strategies. You can add logic to choose the appropriate strategy based on the token type.

```javascript
class TokenManager {
    constructor() {
        this.tokenStrategies = {
            access: null,
            refresh: null,
            apiKey: null,
        };
    }

    setTokenStrategy(type, strategy) {
        if (!(strategy instanceof TokenStrategy)) {
            throw new Error('Provided strategy must be an instance of TokenStrategy');
        }
        this.tokenStrategies[type] = strategy;
    }

    generateToken(type, payload) {
        if (!this.tokenStrategies[type]) {
            throw new Error('Token strategy not defined for type: ' + type);
        }
        return this.tokenStrategies[type].generateToken(payload);
    }

    verifyToken(type, token) {
        if (!this.tokenStrategies[type]) {
            throw new Error('Token strategy not defined for type: ' + type);
        }
        return this.tokenStrategies[type].verifyToken(token);
    }

    blacklistToken(token) {
        // Same blacklisting logic as before
        this.tokenBlacklist.add(token);
    }

    getRateLimitMiddleware() {
        return this.rateLimiter.getMiddleware();
    }
}
```

### Step 4: Usage Example

Finally, you can use the `TokenManager` largely the same way as before, but now specify which token type to generate and verify:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const tokenManager = new TokenManager();
tokenManager.setTokenStrategy('access', new AccessTokenStrategy('access_secret', '1h'));
tokenManager.setTokenStrategy('refresh', new RefreshTokenStrategy('refresh_secret', '7d'));
tokenManager.setTokenStrategy('apiKey', new ApiKeyStrategy('api_key_secret'));

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
    // Authenticate user and generate an access token
    const user = { id: 1, username: 'test' }; // Example user
    const accessToken = tokenManager.generateToken('access', user);
    const refreshToken = tokenManager.generateToken('refresh', { userId: user.id });
    res.json({ accessToken, refreshToken });
});

app.post('/logout', (req, res) => {
    const token = req.headers['authorization'].split(' ')[1];
    tokenManager.blacklistToken(token);
    res.sendStatus(204);
});

app.get('/protected', (req, res) => {
    const token = req.headers['authorization'].split(' ')[1];
    try {
        const userData = tokenManager.verifyToken('access', token);
        res.json({ message: 'Protected data', user: userData });
    } catch (error) {
        res.status(401).json({ error: error.message });
    }
});

app.get('/api-key', (req, res) => {
    const apiKey = tokenManager.generateToken('apiKey', { userId: 1 });
    res.json({ apiKey });
});

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

### Summary

In this implementation, we've used the Strategy pattern to define different token strategies for access tokens, refresh tokens, and API keys. The `TokenManager` interface remains unchanged, allowing existing code to function without breaking. The strategies are interchangeable at runtime, promoting flexibility and maintainability.

